1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,440
Three officers at the door.

2
00:00:02,120 --> 00:00:04,020
A piece of paper waved like a warrant

3
00:00:04,799 --> 00:00:05,740
but no real warrant.

4
00:00:06,380 --> 00:00:07,260
They go in anyway.

5
00:00:07,900 --> 00:00:09,720
And what they find ends up thrown out

6
00:00:09,720 --> 00:00:10,140
of court.

7
00:00:13,940 --> 00:00:15,435
That moment —

8
00:00:15,580 --> 00:00:17,700
police forcing their way into an American

9
00:00:17,700 --> 00:00:21,380
home, the courts later refusing to use what

10
00:00:21,380 --> 00:00:22,835
they turned up —

11
00:00:22,836 --> 00:00:24,940
is not a legal technicality.

12
00:00:25,520 --> 00:00:27,340
It is the answer to one of the

13
00:00:27,340 --> 00:00:31,100
most important questions in criminal law: if

14
00:00:31,100 --> 00:00:33,280
the police break the rules to get evidence

15
00:00:33,280 --> 00:00:36,160
against you, can they still use that

16
00:00:36,160 --> 00:00:37,640
evidence to convict you?

17
00:00:39,060 --> 00:00:41,160
Before 1961, in most states,

18
00:00:41,360 --> 00:00:42,220
the answer was yes.

19
00:00:43,860 --> 00:00:45,760
The Fourth Amendment says the government

20
00:00:45,760 --> 00:00:48,280
cannot conduct unreasonable searches.

21
00:00:48,920 --> 00:00:51,180
It has said that since 1791.

22
00:00:52,140 --> 00:00:53,940
But for most of American history,

23
00:00:54,480 --> 00:00:57,380
the amendment had a problem: no one had

24
00:00:57,380 --> 00:00:59,820
figured out what happened when the police

25
00:00:59,820 --> 00:01:01,011
ignored it .

26
00:01:01,200 --> 00:01:02,560
The evidence was still there.

27
00:01:03,140 --> 00:01:04,420
The conviction still came.

28
00:01:05,080 --> 00:01:06,540
The right existed on paper,

29
00:01:06,540 --> 00:01:07,660
and nowhere else.

30
00:01:09,060 --> 00:01:10,964
What changed that —

31
00:01:11,060 --> 00:01:13,560
what gave the Fourth Amendment actual teeth

32
00:01:13,560 --> 00:01:15,735
in a real courtroom —

33
00:01:15,736 --> 00:01:17,680
was a search gone wrong in Cleveland,

34
00:01:17,820 --> 00:01:21,860
Ohio, in 1957, and a woman named Dollree

35
00:01:21,860 --> 00:01:22,494
Mapp .

36
00:01:23,200 --> 00:01:25,980
Over the next twelve minutes: what happened

37
00:01:25,980 --> 00:01:29,040
at her door, what the Supreme Court did

38
00:01:29,040 --> 00:01:31,400
about it, and why the rule they created

39
00:01:31,400 --> 00:01:33,900
is still the most argued-over protection in

40
00:01:33,900 --> 00:01:35,060
American criminal law.

41
00:01:36,560 --> 00:01:39,133
It is May 23, 1957 .

42
00:01:40,400 --> 00:01:42,520
Dollree Mapp lives on the upper floor of

43
00:01:42,520 --> 00:01:43,940
a house in Cleveland, Ohio.

44
00:01:44,820 --> 00:01:47,260
On that afternoon, Cleveland police officers

45
00:01:47,260 --> 00:01:48,894
arrive at her door .

46
00:01:49,880 --> 00:01:51,820
They are looking for a suspect in a

47
00:01:51,820 --> 00:01:54,026
bombing case —

48
00:01:54,027 --> 00:01:55,240
a man they believe may be hiding in

49
00:01:55,240 --> 00:01:58,057
the house .

50
00:01:58,058 --> 00:01:58,558
They knock.

51
00:01:58,559 --> 00:01:59,660
Mapp does not let them in.

52
00:02:00,180 --> 00:02:01,280
She calls her attorney.

53
00:02:02,020 --> 00:02:03,300
The officers wait outside.

54
00:02:04,600 --> 00:02:07,268
Then they go in anyway .

55
00:02:07,269 --> 00:02:08,920
An officer holds up a piece of paper

56
00:02:10,678 --> 00:02:11,480
waving it as if it were a warrant

57
00:02:11,480 --> 00:02:15,222
authorizing the search .

58
00:02:15,223 --> 00:02:16,660
Mapp grabs for it; the officers take it

59
00:02:16,660 --> 00:02:17,000
back.

60
00:02:18,160 --> 00:02:20,680
Later, no valid warrant will be produced in

61
00:02:20,680 --> 00:02:20,940
court.

62
00:02:21,800 --> 00:02:24,480
Whether one ever existed at all will remain

63
00:02:24,480 --> 00:02:25,827
disputed —

64
00:02:25,828 --> 00:02:28,820
but what is not disputed is this: no

65
00:02:28,820 --> 00:02:31,130
valid warrant was ever shown .

66
00:02:32,060 --> 00:02:33,340
A warrant, to be clear,

67
00:02:33,580 --> 00:02:36,220
is a judge's written authorization for a

68
00:02:36,220 --> 00:02:37,040
specific search.

69
00:02:37,720 --> 00:02:40,100
To get one, police have to show a

70
00:02:40,100 --> 00:02:42,389
judge they have good reason —

71
00:02:42,390 --> 00:02:44,280
what the law calls probable cause.

72
00:02:45,120 --> 00:02:47,140
It is the check on police power the

73
00:02:47,140 --> 00:02:49,500
Fourth Amendment was designed to require.

74
00:02:50,300 --> 00:02:52,220
A piece of paper waved through a window

75
00:02:52,220 --> 00:02:53,060
is not one.

76
00:02:54,640 --> 00:02:56,420
The officers search the house.

77
00:02:57,080 --> 00:02:58,800
They do not find the bombing suspect.

78
00:02:59,660 --> 00:03:01,553
They do find something else —

79
00:03:02,320 --> 00:03:04,589
material they say breaks an Ohio law .

80
00:03:04,960 --> 00:03:07,160
They arrest Dollree Mapp not for anything

81
00:03:07,160 --> 00:03:09,860
related to the bombing, but for what the

82
00:03:09,860 --> 00:03:12,177
warrantless search turned up .

83
00:03:13,100 --> 00:03:16,500
She is tried, convicted, and sentenced under

84
00:03:16,500 --> 00:03:17,805
that Ohio law .

85
00:03:18,360 --> 00:03:19,465
And that conviction —

86
00:03:20,040 --> 00:03:22,370
not any bombing, not the suspect —

87
00:03:22,600 --> 00:03:25,240
is what eventually reaches the Supreme Court

88
00:03:25,240 --> 00:03:26,280
of the United States.

89
00:03:27,760 --> 00:03:30,220
But to get there, first she has to

90
00:03:30,220 --> 00:03:30,480
lose.

91
00:03:31,160 --> 00:03:33,640
And the reason she loses reveals a gap

92
00:03:33,640 --> 00:03:36,100
in American law that most people never knew

93
00:03:36,100 --> 00:03:36,660
existed.

94
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:39,040
Here is the gap.

95
00:03:39,900 --> 00:03:42,220
The Fourth Amendment, as of 1957,

96
00:03:42,680 --> 00:03:44,120
already applied to the states.

97
00:03:44,940 --> 00:03:47,300
A 1949 Supreme Court case,

98
00:03:48,280 --> 00:03:48,640
Wolf v.

99
00:03:49,080 --> 00:03:51,703
Colorado, had settled that much .

100
00:03:52,360 --> 00:03:54,220
States could not conduct unreasonable

101
00:03:54,220 --> 00:03:55,044
searches —

102
00:03:55,560 --> 00:03:56,953
that was clear .

103
00:03:57,480 --> 00:04:00,820
What Wolf had not done was specify what

104
00:04:00,820 --> 00:04:02,516
happened next .

105
00:04:02,660 --> 00:04:04,700
If a state officer conducted an illegal

106
00:04:04,700 --> 00:04:07,080
search and found something, did that

107
00:04:07,080 --> 00:04:08,580
evidence have to be thrown out?

108
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:11,680
Wolf said: not necessarily.

109
00:04:12,740 --> 00:04:14,580
States were free to handle the problem

110
00:04:14,580 --> 00:04:16,256
however they chose .

111
00:04:16,460 --> 00:04:18,880
And many states chose to use the evidence

112
00:04:18,880 --> 00:04:19,260
anyway.

113
00:04:20,660 --> 00:04:22,880
Federal courts had operated under a

114
00:04:22,880 --> 00:04:25,785
different rule since 1914 —

115
00:04:25,786 --> 00:04:27,600
a case called Weeks v.

116
00:04:27,760 --> 00:04:29,296
United States .

117
00:04:29,920 --> 00:04:32,100
Weeks established what lawyers call the

118
00:04:32,100 --> 00:04:35,420
exclusionary rule: evidence obtained through

119
00:04:35,420 --> 00:04:38,040
an illegal search cannot be used in a

120
00:04:38,040 --> 00:04:38,951
federal prosecution .

121
00:04:39,920 --> 00:04:41,180
The logic was simple.

122
00:04:41,760 --> 00:04:43,840
If the government breaks the law to get

123
00:04:43,840 --> 00:04:46,880
evidence, and then uses that evidence to

124
00:04:46,880 --> 00:04:49,800
convict you, the court itself becomes a

125
00:04:49,800 --> 00:04:51,160
participant in the lawbreaking.

126
00:04:52,680 --> 00:04:55,000
But Mapp's case was in a state court,

127
00:04:55,380 --> 00:04:57,919
not a federal one .

128
00:04:57,920 --> 00:04:59,080
And Ohio was one of the states that,

129
00:04:59,500 --> 00:05:01,800
under Wolf, was allowed to use what an

130
00:05:01,800 --> 00:05:05,480
illegal search turned up .

131
00:05:05,481 --> 00:05:05,680
The Fourth Amendment existed.

132
00:05:06,520 --> 00:05:08,700
The search was almost certainly illegal.

133
00:05:09,400 --> 00:05:11,241
And it did not matter .

134
00:05:12,060 --> 00:05:13,160
She is convicted.

135
00:05:13,900 --> 00:05:14,760
Her lawyers appeal.

136
00:05:15,520 --> 00:05:17,500
The Ohio Supreme Court upholds the

137
00:05:17,500 --> 00:05:18,428
conviction .

138
00:05:18,640 --> 00:05:20,480
Then the case goes to Washington.

139
00:05:22,260 --> 00:05:24,140
Her attorneys arrive at the Supreme Court

140
00:05:24,140 --> 00:05:26,580
primarily to argue about whether the state

141
00:05:26,580 --> 00:05:29,220
law she was convicted under was even

142
00:05:29,220 --> 00:05:30,000
constitutional.

143
00:05:30,960 --> 00:05:33,966
The exclusionary rule —

144
00:05:33,967 --> 00:05:35,300
whether the evidence should have been thrown

145
00:05:35,300 --> 00:05:38,061
out —

146
00:05:38,062 --> 00:05:39,100
is raised almost as an afterthought.

147
00:05:40,240 --> 00:05:40,580
Almost.

148
00:05:42,160 --> 00:05:44,360
Because the Supreme Court is about to do

149
00:05:44,360 --> 00:05:46,440
something no one in the courtroom fully

150
00:05:46,440 --> 00:05:47,180
anticipated.

151
00:05:47,960 --> 00:05:50,100
It is about to settle a much larger

152
00:05:50,100 --> 00:05:52,600
question than the one anyone thought they

153
00:05:52,600 --> 00:05:53,220
were arguing.

154
00:05:54,900 --> 00:05:58,160
On June 19, 1961, the Supreme Court issues

155
00:05:58,160 --> 00:05:59,800
its decision in Mapp v.

156
00:05:59,800 --> 00:06:00,760
Ohio .

157
00:06:01,380 --> 00:06:02,480
Justice Tom C.

158
00:06:02,760 --> 00:06:04,240
Clark writes the opinion of the Court,

159
00:06:04,240 --> 00:06:06,198
over three dissents .

160
00:06:07,020 --> 00:06:09,620
The Court does not simply resolve whether

161
00:06:09,620 --> 00:06:11,520
the Ohio law is constitutional.

162
00:06:12,080 --> 00:06:13,920
It reaches back to Wolf v.

163
00:06:13,920 --> 00:06:15,772
Colorado —

164
00:06:15,773 --> 00:06:18,580
the 1949 case that had let states use

165
00:06:18,580 --> 00:06:20,878
illegally seized evidence —

166
00:06:20,879 --> 00:06:23,006
and it overrules it .

167
00:06:23,007 --> 00:06:25,380
After twelve years, the loophole is closed.

168
00:06:26,960 --> 00:06:29,360
The reasoning turns on a single principle.

169
00:06:30,180 --> 00:06:32,640
If the Fourth Amendment is a real right,

170
00:06:33,200 --> 00:06:35,520
there has to be a real remedy when

171
00:06:35,520 --> 00:06:38,137
it is violated .

172
00:06:38,138 --> 00:06:39,776
The exclusionary rule —

173
00:06:39,777 --> 00:06:41,825
throwing out the evidence —

174
00:06:41,826 --> 00:06:41,960
is that remedy.

175
00:06:42,840 --> 00:06:44,520
Without it, the Court says,

176
00:06:45,040 --> 00:06:47,800
the constitutional protection becomes "a

177
00:06:47,800 --> 00:06:48,790
form of words" .

178
00:06:49,380 --> 00:06:52,060
A guarantee that no one can actually use

179
00:06:52,060 --> 00:06:53,040
is not a guarantee.

180
00:06:54,580 --> 00:06:56,680
The point is not to help guilty defendants.

181
00:06:57,420 --> 00:06:59,720
The point is to deter the police from

182
00:06:59,720 --> 00:07:03,640
breaking the law in the first place —

183
00:07:03,641 --> 00:07:04,020
and to keep the courts from becoming

184
00:07:04,020 --> 00:07:08,056
instruments of constitutional violations .

185
00:07:08,057 --> 00:07:09,360
If you want to use evidence,

186
00:07:10,160 --> 00:07:10,680
get a warrant.

187
00:07:11,560 --> 00:07:12,320
Follow the rules.

188
00:07:13,080 --> 00:07:15,140
Do not force your way in with a

189
00:07:15,140 --> 00:07:15,860
piece of paper.

190
00:07:17,520 --> 00:07:20,160
The holding is straightforward: illegally

191
00:07:20,160 --> 00:07:22,111
seized evidence is thrown out —

192
00:07:22,500 --> 00:07:24,840
the exclusionary rule now applies to the

193
00:07:24,840 --> 00:07:25,820
states .

194
00:07:26,060 --> 00:07:28,280
Every state court in the country is now

195
00:07:28,280 --> 00:07:30,680
bound by the same rule that federal courts

196
00:07:30,680 --> 00:07:34,884
had operated under since 1914 .

197
00:07:34,885 --> 00:07:37,769
Where most criminal cases actually happen —

198
00:07:37,770 --> 00:07:39,417
in state courtrooms —

199
00:07:39,418 --> 00:07:41,360
the Fourth Amendment finally has a

200
00:07:41,360 --> 00:07:42,713
consequence .

201
00:07:43,960 --> 00:07:45,945
Dollree Mapp's conviction is reversed .

202
00:07:46,400 --> 00:07:48,560
The search that started it all is ruled

203
00:07:48,560 --> 00:07:50,960
to have violated her constitutional rights,

204
00:07:51,540 --> 00:07:53,760
and the evidence from that search cannot be

205
00:07:53,760 --> 00:07:55,142
used against her .

206
00:07:55,920 --> 00:07:57,620
It is a resounding win.

207
00:07:58,160 --> 00:08:00,260
And it carries a cost that no one

208
00:08:00,260 --> 00:08:00,840
can ignore.

209
00:08:02,460 --> 00:08:05,020
The exclusionary rule does something that

210
00:08:05,020 --> 00:08:06,820
has troubled people ever since it was

211
00:08:06,820 --> 00:08:07,380
created.

212
00:08:08,280 --> 00:08:10,200
It can require a court to throw out

213
00:08:10,200 --> 00:08:12,082
reliable evidence —

214
00:08:12,180 --> 00:08:14,860
evidence that is true, that demonstrates

215
00:08:14,860 --> 00:08:15,502
what happened —

216
00:08:15,640 --> 00:08:18,541
because of the way it was obtained .

217
00:08:19,580 --> 00:08:22,760
In 1926, a New York judge named Benjamin

218
00:08:22,760 --> 00:08:25,900
Cardozo put the objection as bluntly as it

219
00:08:25,900 --> 00:08:26,540
can be put.

220
00:08:27,160 --> 00:08:29,140
If the police bungle a search,

221
00:08:29,260 --> 00:08:32,080
he wrote, "the criminal is to go free

222
00:08:32,080 --> 00:08:35,287
because the constable has blundered" .

223
00:08:35,288 --> 00:08:37,900
The guilty person walks not because the

224
00:08:37,900 --> 00:08:40,840
evidence was wrong, but because the process

225
00:08:40,840 --> 00:08:42,923
that produced it was .

226
00:08:43,800 --> 00:08:46,500
That tension is real and it has never

227
00:08:46,500 --> 00:08:47,160
gone away.

228
00:08:48,380 --> 00:08:50,220
Defenders of the rule argue that the

229
00:08:50,220 --> 00:08:52,717
deterrence is worth the cost —

230
00:08:52,718 --> 00:08:55,480
that without the consequence, there is no

231
00:08:55,480 --> 00:08:57,640
reason for police to respect the warrant

232
00:08:57,640 --> 00:08:59,526
requirement at all .

233
00:09:00,200 --> 00:09:01,980
Critics argue that the cure sometimes

234
00:09:01,980 --> 00:09:04,640
punishes society more than it punishes the

235
00:09:04,640 --> 00:09:06,713
officer who made the mistake .

236
00:09:07,580 --> 00:09:10,120
The Supreme Court itself has spent decades

237
00:09:10,120 --> 00:09:11,560
navigating that tension.

238
00:09:12,180 --> 00:09:13,660
It has not stayed still.

239
00:09:14,680 --> 00:09:16,620
Later rulings carved out limits and

240
00:09:16,620 --> 00:09:19,043
exceptions to what Mapp established —

241
00:09:19,640 --> 00:09:21,680
among them a good-faith exception,

242
00:09:21,680 --> 00:09:25,220
for cases where officers acted on a warrant

243
00:09:25,220 --> 00:09:27,360
they reasonably believed was valid,

244
00:09:27,360 --> 00:09:29,700
even if it turned out to be defective

245
00:09:30,380 --> 00:09:33,020
The rule today is narrower than it was

246
00:09:33,020 --> 00:09:34,900
in 1961 .

247
00:09:36,080 --> 00:09:37,820
But the core holds.

248
00:09:37,820 --> 00:09:40,100
An illegal search can still sink a case

249
00:09:40,100 --> 00:09:42,152
in state court .

250
00:09:42,153 --> 00:09:44,460
The warrant requirement still has

251
00:09:45,460 --> 00:09:45,520
consequences.

252
00:09:45,520 --> 00:09:47,152
Mapp is the reason for that .

253
00:09:48,320 --> 00:09:50,659
What the case really established —

254
00:09:51,420 --> 00:09:54,200
what makes it more than an obscure

255
00:09:54,200 --> 00:09:54,721
procedural ruling —

256
00:09:55,900 --> 00:09:58,520
is that rights without remedies are

257
00:09:59,240 --> 00:09:59,540
fictions.

258
00:09:59,540 --> 00:10:02,940
The Fourth Amendment had existed for a

259
00:10:02,940 --> 00:10:05,380
hundred and seventy years before Mapp.

260
00:10:05,380 --> 00:10:07,460
It took a forced entry,

261
00:10:07,920 --> 00:10:10,940
a piece of paper waved as a warrant,

262
00:10:10,940 --> 00:10:11,376
and one woman's conviction to make it real

263
00:10:11,482 --> 00:10:13,407
in a state courtroom .

264
00:10:13,980 --> 00:10:15,820
Step back from the facts,

265
00:10:16,200 --> 00:10:18,400
and the shape of this case is almost

266
00:10:18,400 --> 00:10:18,740
counterintuitive.

267
00:10:20,300 --> 00:10:22,160
The landmark that reshaped

268
00:10:22,160 --> 00:10:24,880
search-and-seizure law in every state did

269
00:10:24,880 --> 00:10:27,240
not begin with a dramatic confrontation.

270
00:10:28,120 --> 00:10:30,680
It began with a bombing suspect who was

271
00:10:30,680 --> 00:10:33,320
never found, a search that produced

272
00:10:33,320 --> 00:10:36,460
something else entirely, and a conviction

273
00:10:36,460 --> 00:10:38,600
that no one at the time thought would

274
00:10:38,600 --> 00:10:40,176
matter very much .

275
00:10:40,680 --> 00:10:42,060
And yet it did.

276
00:10:42,960 --> 00:10:44,402
Mapp, Gideon, Miranda —

277
00:10:46,080 --> 00:10:48,540
these three cases are not coincidences

278
00:10:48,540 --> 00:10:49,960
stacked next to each other.

279
00:10:50,620 --> 00:10:52,660
They are three pieces of the same shift:

280
00:10:53,300 --> 00:10:55,500
applying your constitutional rights to the

281
00:10:55,500 --> 00:10:58,320
states, making them real where you actually

282
00:10:58,320 --> 00:10:58,498
encounter the law .

283
00:11:00,440 --> 00:11:02,500
Miranda told police what they have to say

284
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:03,480
when they arrest you.

285
00:11:04,280 --> 00:11:06,760
Gideon guaranteed you a lawyer if you cannot

286
00:11:06,760 --> 00:11:07,400
afford one.

287
00:11:08,300 --> 00:11:10,520
Mapp answered what happens when the police

288
00:11:10,520 --> 00:11:12,985
break the rules before any of that .

289
00:11:13,960 --> 00:11:15,680
The Fourth Amendment says the government

290
00:11:15,680 --> 00:11:17,340
cannot search your home without

291
00:11:17,340 --> 00:11:18,120
justification.

292
00:11:19,380 --> 00:11:21,340
Mapp is the answer to the follow-up question

293
00:11:21,340 --> 00:11:24,780
nobody asked loudly enough for decades: or

294
00:11:24,780 --> 00:11:25,120
what?

295
00:11:26,340 --> 00:11:28,420
Or the evidence gets thrown out.

296
00:11:28,840 --> 00:11:29,760
That is the rule.

297
00:11:30,360 --> 00:11:31,760
That is what the case cost,

298
00:11:31,760 --> 00:11:32,880
and what it bought.

299
00:11:33,900 --> 00:11:36,514
Next episode: we pull back further —

300
00:11:36,520 --> 00:11:39,500
to who decides what counts as a crime

301
00:11:39,500 --> 00:11:42,140
in the first place, and whether the law

302
00:11:42,140 --> 00:11:44,400
applies to the people who write it.

303
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:47,480
Until then: now you know what it took

304
00:11:47,480 --> 00:11:49,400
to make the Fourth Amendment more than

305
00:11:49,400 --> 00:11:49,780
words.
